{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1782776842,"nonce":"M+Yqvy9Wr4Dvak1zgNAfBGlOW0Q=","message":"Increment 1 — frame clauses (ROWS/RANGE BETWEEN) — shipped in #65 (squash a093edd).\n\nfunc(...) OVER (... ROWS|RANGE BETWEEN \u003cstart\u003e AND \u003cend\u003e) via Window::rows/range, with:\n- a Frame typestate (default NoFrame) so a frame is written last and at most once (compile-fail: window_rejects_second_frame);\n- typed bounds — FrameStart/FrameEnd marker traits, constructors unbounded_preceding()/preceding(n)/current_row()/following(n)/unbounded_following() — rejecting wrong-side bounds at compile time (compile-fail: window_rejects_unbounded_following_as_frame_start), with the deserializer enforcing the same side-validity;\n- literal bounds ⇒ no bind params; one shared FrameSpec::render across the query renderer, test backend, and view renderer (no Dialect seam — PG and MySQL 8.0+ share the syntax); frame threaded through the view model + KDL round-trip.\n\nThe start-after-end ordering rule (e.g. preceding(1) vs preceding(5)) is a runtime numeric comparison left to the database, by design.\n\nRemaining: Increment 2 — the named WINDOW clause (SELECT … OVER w … WINDOW w AS (…)), which touches the select sink rather than just the expr. Tracked as its own follow-up; keeping this bug open for it.","files":null}]}